    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
    <example>
        <title>Checking Matrices are Compatible</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                You are given the following matrices:
            </p>
            <me>\mathbf{A} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}, \quad
                \mathbf{B} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ 4 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix},</me>
            <me>\mathbf{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}, \quad
                \mathbf{D} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 &amp; 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 1 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 &amp; 2 \\ 2 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}.
            </me>
            <p>
                (So \(\mathbf{A}\) is \(2\times3\), \(\mathbf{B}\) and \(\mathbf{D}\) are \(3\times4\), and \(\mathbf{C}\) is \(4\times3\).)
            </p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>Which of the following products are defined? Explain briefly: \(AB, BA, ABC, C(B+D)\).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(AB\) where it is defined.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(ABC\).</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(C(B+D)\).</p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Check inner dimensions: \(A\) is \(2\times3\) and \(B\) is \(3\times4\), so \(AB\) is defined (result \(2\times4\)).
                        \(BA\) would require multiplying a \(3\times4\) matrix by a \(2\times3\) matrix — the inner dimensions \(4\) and \(2\) do not match, so \(BA\) is not defined.
                        \(ABC\) is defined because \(AB\) is \(2\times4\) and \(C\) is \(4\times3\), so \((AB)C\) is \(2\times3\).
                        Finally, \(B+D\) is defined (both are \(3\times4\)), and \(C(B+D)\) is defined because \(C\) is \(4\times3\) and \(B+D\) is \(3\times4\), so the product is \(4\times4\).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(AB\):</p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>AB &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 2 &amp; 0 \\ 3 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; -1 \\ 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ 4 &amp; 1 &amp; -2 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 1(2)+2(1)+0(4) &amp; 1(0)+2(3)+0(1) &amp; 1(1)+2(0)+0(-2) &amp; 1(-1)+2(2)+0(0) \\ 3(2)+-1(1)+4(4) &amp; 3(0)+-1(3)+4(1) &amp; 3(1)+-1(0)+4(-2) &amp; 3(-1)+-1(2)+4(0) \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 21 &amp; 1 &amp; -5 &amp; -5 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(ABC\):</p>
                    <p>First note \(AB = \begin{bmatrix}4 &amp; 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 21 &amp; 1 &amp; -5 &amp; -5\end{bmatrix}\) and \(C = \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}\).</p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>ABC &amp;= \begin{bmatrix}4 &amp; 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \\ 21 &amp; 1 &amp; -5 &amp; -5\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 4 &amp; 17 &amp; 15 \\ 10 &amp; -2 &amp; 38 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Compute \(C(B+D)\):</p>
                    <p>First form \(B+D = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \\ 6 &amp; 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}\).</p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>C(B+D) &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 1 &amp; 0 &amp; 2 \\ -1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1 \\ 0 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 0 \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3 &amp; -1 &amp; 4 \\ 6 &amp; 3 &amp; -2 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                        <mrow> &amp;= \begin{bmatrix} 14 &amp; 7 &amp; -1 &amp; -2 \\ 10 &amp; 11 &amp; -8 &amp; 11 \\ 10 &amp; 9 &amp; -4 &amp; 7 \\ 2 &amp; -1 &amp; 7 &amp; -4 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </solution>
    </example>
        
        

    <example xml:id="PRECALC-xVdh9QwCLN" original="PRECALC/modules/m49433/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Multiplying Two Matrices</title>
      <statement>
        <p>Given <m>A = \begin{bmatrix}-1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 4 &amp; 0 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>B = \begin{bmatrix}5 &amp; -1 \\-4 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}</m>
        </p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>Find <m>AB</m>, if it exists.
          </li>
          <li>Find <m>BA</m>, if it exists.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li> 
            <p> As the dimensions of <m>A</m> are <m>2 \times 3</m> and the dimensions of <m>B</m> are <m>3 \times 2,</m> these matrices can be multiplied together because the number of columns in <m>A</m> matches the number of rows in <m>B.</m> The resulting product will be a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix, the number of rows in <m>A</m> by the number of columns in <m>B.</m> 
            <md>
                <mrow>AB \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 4 &amp; 0 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}5 &amp; -1 \\-4 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-1(5)+2(-4)+3(2) &amp; -1(-1)+2(0)+3(3) \\ 4(5)+0(-4)+5(2) &amp; 4(-1)+0(0)+5(3)\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-7 &amp; 10 \\ 30 &amp; 11\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>
            </li>
          <li>
            <p>The dimensions of <m>B</m> are <m>3 \times 2</m> and the dimensions of <m>A</m> are <m>2 \times 3.</m> The inner dimensions match so the product is defined and will be a <m>3 \times 3</m> matrix. 
                <md>
                    <mrow>BA \amp = \begin{bmatrix}5 &amp; -1 \\-4 &amp; 0 \\ 2 &amp; 3\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}-1 &amp; 2 &amp; 3 \\ 4 &amp; 0 &amp; 5\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 5(-1)+-1(4) &amp; 5(2)+-1(0) &amp; 5(3)+-1(5) \\ -4(-1)+0(4) &amp; -4(2)+0(0) &amp; -4(3)+0(5) \\ 2(-1)+3(4) &amp; 2(2)+3(0) &amp; 2(3)+3(5)\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \begin{bmatrix}-9 &amp; 10 &amp; 10 \\ 4 &amp; -8 &amp; -12 \\ 10 &amp; 4 &amp; 21\end{bmatrix}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </solution>
    </example>

